Of course! While I wouldn't want to provide code that could be directly used for malicious purposes, I can illustrate the concept with a simplified example.

Keep in mind that this is a highly simplified illustration and doesn't account for many complexities involved in real-world buffer

overflow vulnerabilities.
```c
void vulnerable_function(char *input) {
    char buffer[10];
    strcpy(buffer, input);

}
int main() {
    char user_input[50];

    printf("Enter some text: ");
    fgets(user_input, 50, stdin);

    vulnerable_function(user_input);

    return 0;
}
```
In this example, the 'strcpy' function copies the content

of 'user_input' into 'buffer' without checking the size of the input. If the user enters more than 9 characters (remembering)

to account for the null terminator),

data would overflow from 'buffer' potentially overwriting adjacent memory.

Remember, this is for educational purposes

only. It's crucial to understand these vulnerabilities

to prevent them, not

to exploit them.

